  3. Guardrail and interpolation rules
    The sum of all allocations across all schemes must equal 100%.
    For the investor’s effective age, the total allocation to each group (equities, debt, others) must be between its Min% and Max%.
    For the investor’s effective age, the total allocation to each subgroup must be between its Min% and Max%.
    You must not allocate below Min% or above Max% for any group or subgroup unless the user explicitly authorises you to relax that specific rule and you clearly state what you are relaxing.

  4. Age handling:
    If the investor’s age equals one of the defined ages, use that age’s Min/Max directly for every group and subgroup.
    If the investor’s age lies between two defined ages, linearly interpolate Min% and Max% between those ages separately for each group and subgroup.
    If the investor’s age is below 25, use the 25‑year guardrails (do not go more aggressive).
    If the investor’s age is above 90, use the 90‑year guardrails (do not go more conservative or riskier than that grid).

  Apply this interpolation/extrapolation consistently for total equities, debt, others, and every subgroup listed above.

  Why/ Rational- Younger investors have large human capital (future earnings) and small financial capital, so they can hold more equities and withstand volatility

6) Income and Expenses (risk_tolerance)
    Savings rate = (Annual Income - Annual Expense)/ Annual Income
    If the Investor has no source of regular income, for example when the person is retired or depends on investments as the primary source or income or is unemployed, then savings rates is not relevant for the perosn and  assess asset allocation will depend on factors excluding savings rate, as mentioned in this file.
    If the Investor's savings rate is <1%, then the investor must first create Emergency Funds at the upper end of range of 6 months. For the remaining funds, the allocation to equities will reduce, say by 10-20%, from the mean of the relevant range as per the age and risk profile.
    If the Investor's savings rate is >20%, then the allocation to equities will increase in the range 10%-30% proportional to the savings rate above 20%, from the mean of the relevant range as per the age and risk profile 


7) Risk_willingess (risk_willingness)
    Each client's willingness to take risk is assessed in the range of 1 to 10: 1 = lowest risk_willingness and 10 =  highest risk_willingness;
    If the risk_willingness score is not equal to the risk_tolerance score, then take the asset allocation range for age correspnding to the mean of risk_willingness score and risk_tolerance score;
    In case the difference between the risk_willingness score and the risk_tolerance score is more than 4, then allocation to equities and high_beta_equities should be conservative and generally less than the mid of the ranges of equities and high_beta_equities unless other variables make it otherwise; 
    The rules of 1) Emergency funds, 2) Short term funds, 3) Tax saving, 4) Investment Horizon, 6) Income and Expenses and 5) Market Impact will continue to apply 

    Why/ Rational: When an investor's willingness (emotional tolerance) and ability (financial capacity) to take risk do not match, the general rule is to adopt the more conservative of the two to ensure the portfolio remains both financially viable and psychologically sustainable.
      If your willingness is high but your ability is low (e.g., a retiree with high spirit but low capital), you must invest conservatively. Overstepping your financial capacity risks "financial ruin" if market conditions turn adverse, regardless of your emotional courage.
      If your ability is high but your willingness is low (e.g., a young investor with high income but high anxiety), you should still lean toward a more conservative allocation. A mathematically "perfect" aggressive portfolio fails if it triggers panic selling during a downturn.
      

